human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'As KDLT and KSFY each celebrate their 60th anniversary in 2020, a new era of local news is starting with Dakota News Now. Susan McGowan was the first female newscaster in Sioux Falls. Her family started KSOO before the station became KSFY, but she was never involved in the operations. She was working at a travel agency next door to the station when one of the anchors popped over and asked if she wanted to do the noon newscast over her lunch break. She agreed to it and was paid $5 per show. "The impact on me was probably just a really bad case of nervousness once they told me that this was the first time a woman had done an anchor," McGowan said. "I didn\'t think of myself as anything other than who I was. I wasn\'t treated like anybody else. Nobody babied me or anything like that." She eventually moved to the evening news where she worked with Tom Rooney. "It\'s been fun to watch from my perspective to see the advancements, especially in the last several years here, where KSFY has really been on the cutting edge of some new technology," Rooney said. McGowan and Rooney said a lot has changed in the news industry since they started in the 1970\'s. "The whole world is faster than it used to be, so I don\'t know how today you do that," McGowan said. "You just have to keep moving, I assume." It is faster and KSFY and KDLT are trying to keep up by doing something McGowan and Rooney never thought would happen. "This is unheard of. Regulatory environment didn\'t allow for that when we were in business, and you didn\'t ever think about that happening because it wouldn\'t, and it wouldn\'t have been allowed. It was illegal," they said. As KDLT and KSFY become one, we\'re carving our own path, looking back on where we started and looking forward to what\'s ahead for Dakota News Now and the opportunities it\'s bringing to viewers.'}]

human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Saturday, June 1, 2024 Evidence overwhelmingly supports the position that U.S. soldiers continued shooting and killing innocent Lakota children, women and men until nightfall on December 29, 1890. That mostly clear day, the temperature reached 66 degrees before the sunset at 4:23 PM. Then the U.S. soldiers departed the killing fields of Wounded Knee to return to their garrison at Pine Ridge some 15 miles west. Along the way, a brilliant moon just three nights past full rose at 7:43 PM to illuminate their journey. It was after 9:30 PM when they finally reached their destination. In their caravan were dead and wounded soldiers, as well as wounded Lakotas. The wounded were laid on the straw strewn floor of Holy Cross Episcopal Church. The pews had been quickly removed and the nave just as swiftly converted from a place of worship to a field hospital. The attending physician was Charles Eastman, a Santee citizen. Photographs show that Christmas garlands still hung near the altar, as did the words, “Peace on Earth, Good Will Toward Men.” On Tuesday, December 30, 1890, the sun rose at 7:21 AM. Just over three hours later, the moon descended beneath the western horizon. The temperature rose to 57 degrees before the sun set at 4:24 PM. The temperature dropped to 30 degrees that night. New Year’s Eve, 1890, the sun rose at 7:22 AM and the moon rose at 10:53 AM. Its illumination was 74%, but it is unlikely anyone at Pine Ridge or Wounded Knee saw it. Snow and Continued from A1 high winds began in the morning, causing blizzard conditions throughout the day. The high temperature was only 38 degrees, then fell to 23 degrees before midnight. On New Year’s, 1891, the sun rose at 7:22 AM and perhaps was witnessed, since the blizzard had ended overnight. The day was partly cloudy. The temperature rose to 32 degrees before falling to 12 degrees that night. Charles Eastman, the physician at Pine Ridge, wrote “We feared that some of the Indian wounded might have been left on the field, and a number of us volunteered to go and see. I was placed in charge of the expedition of about a hundred civilians, ten or fifteen of whom were white men. We were supplied with wagons in which to convey any whom we might find still alive. Of course, a photographer and several reporters were of the party.” One can imagine the pain and anger felt by Dr. Eastman when he also wrote, “Fully three miles from the scene of the massacre we found the body of a woman completely covered with a blanket of snow, and from this point on we found them scattered along as they had been relentlessly hunted down and slaughtered while fleeing for their lives.” Eleven persons were found alive and transported to Pine Ridge. The expedition photographers took the first photographs of the massacre site, and those photos are the ones that continue to contribute to the inaccurate belief that the day of the massacre was cold and snowy. Friday, January 2, 1891, was mostly clear. The temperature rose to 46 degrees after a 7:22 AM sunrise. The sun set at 4:26 PM and the temperature plummeted to 9 degrees overnight. The first weekend of 1891, the high temperatures were in the mid- 40s; the low temperature was 17 degrees on Saturday and 24 degrees on Sunday. Over the course of those two days, a group of hired civilians buried the Lakota bodies that remained at Wounded Knee. They dug a trench 6 feet wide, 72 feet long, and 5 feet deep. The contractor received $2 for each of the bodies of 18 children, 44 women and 84 men that were dropped in the grave. Soon thereafter, Luther Standing Bear rode his horse to Wounded Knee. “It was early in the morning when I reached this place, and the silence was oppressive and terrible,” he recalled. “The place of death was forsaken and forbidding. I stood there in silence for several minutes, in reverence for the dead, and then turned and rode toward the agency.” Center for American Indian Research and Native Studies (CAIRNS) is an Indian-controlled nonprofit research and education center founded in 2004 and located in the Lacreek District of Pine Ridge Reservation in South Dakota.
